8/8 There are over a quarter of a million people in Ireland with diabetes, over half a billion worldwide, a lifelong condition listed by @WHO as one of the top ten leading causes of deaths globally. And the rates are increasing year on year.

6/8 In Ireland the HSE supplies this device to Type 1 Diabetics (but we need to do more to extend to Type 2 that need it). A great diabetic nurse at the #bonssecours gave me a tutorial today and now i canâ€™t stop checking my phone.. and not to check up on social media ğŸ˜… @dexcom

5/8 It monitors my glucose continuously and sends it via bluetooth to an app on my phone that gives me up to the minute data - and also sends it on to my diabetic health care team. It alerts me if my bloods are going too low or too high and no more impromtu fainting hopefully ğŸ˜Š

The light installation was so important to him. Yet if you analyse it â€“ decompose it - what it amounts to is a light shining through pinpricks on paper. But the key is the light â€“ the illumination.

It was during one of those long moments of silence that Richard paused and said â€œI believe in star dustâ€ â€“ it was a phrase that he repeated often after that â€“ a sort of mantra that gave him the grit to see through those terrible days
Dara would try to tell him something funny - trying to find normality in the tragic circumstances that led to his wonderful strong dad making that painful journey. Sometimes we ran out of words.

Some evenings we remained there for 30 minutes or more as he steadfastly made his way purposefully up those stairs â€“ refusing all offers of help. Most of these journeys would begin with Dara and myself encouraging him, distracting him.

Richard had cancer in most of his major organs but it was the cancer in his spine that was the most debilitating
And as it became harder for him to climb those stairs he would stare at that installation as he paused to catch his breath and gather his strength to take another step

In my house I have this light installation by artist Oisin Byrne called â€œwe are stardustâ€.  Itâ€™s a magical recreation of two people intertwined in starlight and it has always lived at the top of the stairs leading to our bedroom.

Knowing that his time was short, Richard became increasingly fond of the idea of stardust, a comfort that he would re-join the cosmos from whence he came. Sending hugs to all who live with and beyond cancer and those, like me, who miss the stars we have lost  #worldcancerday https://t.co/u5rjTKaAhd
